    <strong>Any doubts? We got you!</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>I don’t feel comfortable carrying a bag with me to collect my trash in public. (waste challenge)</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    It is important to actually carry the bag around because:
  </p>
  <p>
    1) you can see the physical accumulation of your trash
  </p>
  <p>
    2) you will experience the burden of your waste, and
  </p>
  <p>
    3) you can't ignore the amount of waste you produce.
  </p>
  <p>
    We recognize it can feel uncomfortable when people look at us and our bag of trash. (We know; we’ve done it!) However, let them look. If they ask you about it, tell them about the challenge you’re doing. Or volunteer this info, even if they don’t
    ask. And ask them: do you know how much trash you produce in a day?
  </p>
  <p>
    This challenge also helps you build confidence in speaking up to stand for what you believe in and care about. However, if you’re not ready, we offered an alternative challenge to accomplish the same goal of auditing your waste.
  </p>
  <p>
    Know that you’re not alone; we are here to support you, and many others are also facing the same challenges. We are here for you and we believe in you. You can do this!!
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>I don’t feel comfortable reaching out to individuals, a business, or local government.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    We recognize people's comfort with speaking to people, especially strangers, varies widely. For many, this challenge can be very daunting.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start small first.
  </p>
  <p>
    For strangers, farmers, and other individuals: smile and/or say ‘hi’.
  </p>
  <p>
    For individuals with authoritative positions (e.g. land management team): email or call.
  </p>
  <p>
    For businesses: email or call a manager.
  </p>
  <p>
    For local government: sit in a city council meeting.
  </p>
  <p>
    And work your way up to speaking to individuals in person, having conversations with them, and maybe even presenting to a larger audience when you’re ready.
  </p>
  <p>
    Remember this: you have every right to ask questions to learn more, voice your concerns and be part of the local government processes as a consumer and citizen. Do not let the fear of what other people think stop you from exploring your curiosities
    and standing up for your values.
  </p>
  <p>
    Your target audience may refuse or make it very difficult to cooperate. Don’t let this bring you down. Instead, be proud! Because you spoke up. You tried to collaborate with them to better your community, and that counts. Try again with them if you
    think something valuable will come out of it. Or, try reaching out to another individual.
  </p>
  <p>
    We're here to support you in this endeavor, so please reach out if you have any questions or need support. We are here for you and we believe in you. You can do this!!
  </p>
